<task id="044" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5">
  <metadata>
    <title>D3-05 Lessons-learned + R6 backlog</title>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>4 hours</estimated-effort>
    <actual-effort></actual-effort>
    <assigned>AI Agent + Operator (collaborative)</assigned>
    <started></started>
    <completed></completed>
    <phase>Phase 3 — Polish + Future-Use Validation</phase>
    <wave>P3-3 (serial; final non-wrap-up content task; blocks 090)</wave>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
    <dependencies>043</dependencies>
    <tags>documentation, lessons-learned, r6-backlog, closeout</tags>
    <rigor-level>STANDARD</rigor-level>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Author the R5 lessons-learned wrap-up document per CLAUDE.md §7 convention. This is
    the project's closeout knowledge-capture artifact. It captures (a) lessons learned
    across all three R5 phases (Phase 1 Platform Extensions, Phase 2 Vertical Slice +
    Insights Tool Integration, Phase 3 Polish + Future-Use Validation), (b) surprises —
    things that did NOT go as planned (contract negotiation outcomes, schema-plumbing
    spike results, BFF publish-size deltas, Structured Outputs streaming behavior,
    tool-routing disambiguation observations, Wave F coordination timing, etc.),
    (c) the R6 backlog — deferred items and net-new candidates surfaced during R5
    execution (Tier 3 file grounding, editor widget, extracted-text widget, additional
    playbooks, any UR-01..UR-05 items not closed, testing-pass findings carried forward
    from task 043).

    This is a documentation-only task: no code, no quality gates. The AI agent drafts
    the document by reading task evidence across all completed R5 task notes + the task
    043 testing-pass results; the operator reviews + adds personal observations
    (especially in the "surprises" section where lived experience matters more than
    artifact mining). Once the operator signs off, the project status is ready to flip
    to Complete — task 090 handles the actual flip + PR + merge.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Technical writer + AI engineering retrospective facilitator. Capable of mining task
    notes, PR descriptions, and coordination logs to synthesize cross-phase patterns
    and producing a balanced retrospective document that captures wins, surprises, and
    forward-looking R6 backlog items. Operates collaboratively with the project
    operator — drafts and structures, then yields to the operator for personal
    observations and final sign-off.
  </role>

  <goal>
    `projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/lessons-learned.md` exists and
    contains four explicit sections: (1) Lessons by phase — what worked, what was
    discovered, what would be done differently next time, organized per phase; (2)
    Surprises — explicit list of things that did NOT go as planned, with root-cause
    framing; (3) R6 backlog candidates — deferred items, UR-01..UR-05 items not closed,
    testing-pass severity-2/3 findings carried forward, and net-new ideas; (4) Operator
    observations — section where the operator's personal observations are added during
    review. The operator has reviewed the document and signed off. Project status is
    ready for task 090 to flip to Complete.
  </goal>

  <inputs>
    <file purpose="project-claude">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/CLAUDE.md</file>
    <file purpose="project-plan">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/plan.md</file>
    <file purpose="project-spec">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/spec.md</file>
    <file purpose="project-design">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/design.md</file>
    <file purpose="task-index">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md</file>
    <file purpose="testing-pass-results">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/testing-pass-results.md</file>
    <file purpose="task-evidence-folder">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/</file>
    <file purpose="coordination-log">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/insights-r2-coordination.md</file>
    <file purpose="insights-contract">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/insights-engine-assistant-integration-brief.md</file>
    <file purpose="insights-v1.1-negotiation">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/insights-engine-contract-v1.1-request.md</file>
    <file purpose="root-claude">CLAUDE.md</file>
  </inputs>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="CLAUDE.md §7">Lessons-learned doc is the closeout artifact convention; produced before the wrap-up task (090) flips project status to Complete. Task 044 produces the artifact; task 090 reads it as evidence + flips status.</constraint>
    <constraint source="R5 project rigor">This is a documentation-only task — rigor STANDARD per CLAUDE.md §8 decision tree. Quality gates (code-review + adr-check) at Step 9.5 are SKIPPED. No BFF code modified → no publish-size measurement. No Dataverse changes → no deploy verification.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">Lessons-learned MUST cover ALL THREE phases (Phase 1 Platform Extensions, Phase 2 Vertical Slice + Insights Tool Integration, Phase 3 Polish + Future-Use Validation) — not just Phase 3.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">Surprises section MUST explicitly document things that did NOT go as planned. Be candid — this is the highest-leverage section for R6 planning. Cover contract-negotiation outcomes (Wave F v1.1 spike result), schema-plumbing decisions (`citations[].href`), BFF publish-size deltas vs the +0.5 MB target, Structured Outputs behavior vs expectation (D1-06), tool-routing disambiguation observations from task 030/031/043, any other unexpected outcomes captured in task notes.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">R6 backlog MUST explicitly enumerate (a) Tier 3 file grounding (large-doc summarization on uploaded files exceeding context window — deferred per R5 scope); (b) editor widget (deferred per design.md); (c) extracted-text widget (deferred per design.md); (d) additional playbooks beyond Summarize + analyze (configuration-only follow-ons); (e) any UR-01..UR-05 items not closed during R5; (f) testing-pass findings carried forward from task 043 by severity.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">Operator-collaboration pattern: AI drafts; operator reviews + adds personal observations in the dedicated "Operator observations" section. The doc is NOT complete until operator review is recorded.</constraint>
    <constraint source="repo path drift">Use `infrastructure/ai-search/` paths in any file references (NOT the legacy `infra/ai-search/` form). Confirmed canonical path for Bicep + index JSON.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">No new code introduced. No tests added. No build/test execution required. The acceptance gate is operator review + sign-off.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <topic>project-closeout/retrospective</topic>
    <files>
      <file>CLAUDE.md (root §7 task completion + transition convention)</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/CLAUDE.md (§7 cross-project awareness; §11 pointers including lessons-learned location)</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/plan.md (D3-05 deliverable description; high-risk items table; phase-gating criteria)</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/spec.md (FR/NFR/DR/PR enumeration; success criteria; UR-01..UR-05 if defined)</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/design.md (vision; reuse mandate §2.11; phasing §7; deferred items noted as R6 candidates)</file>
    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern name="Lessons-learned section structure" location="prior project lessons-learned files (e.g., projects/ai-spaarke-insights-engine-r2/notes/lessons-learned.md if present)">
        Conventional shape: (a) executive summary, (b) lessons by phase, (c) surprises,
        (d) R6 backlog (forward-looking deferred items + new candidates), (e) operator
        observations section. Each lesson is a tight 2–4 sentence vignette: what
        happened, why it mattered, what to do differently. Surprises are NOT softened
        — explicit "did NOT go as planned" framing surfaces process debt.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Evidence-mining across task notes" location="projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/">
        Walk every `task-NNN-*.md` evidence file produced during R5 execution. Extract:
        publish-size deltas (per-task verification per CLAUDE.md §10 + ADR-029); ADR
        compliance observations from Step 9.5 quality gates; coordination touchpoints
        documented in `insights-r2-coordination.md` §8 changelog; smoke-test results
        from task 030 + 031 + 043; D1–D6 Insights contract decisions recorded in §10
        review log (cross-worktree); any blockers / escalations / human-input events.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="R6 backlog framing" location="design.md §7 phasing + spec.md Open Decisions">
        Items explicitly marked "deferred to R6" or "deferred to Phase 1 spike" in
        spec/design are the backlog seed. Add testing-pass findings (task 043) carried
        forward by severity. Add net-new candidates surfaced during R5 execution.
        Format: ID + 1-sentence intent + driver + suggested phase placement
        (foundational / capability / polish).
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      R5 ran ~2.5–3 weeks across 3 phases + wrap-up, decomposed into 31 implementation
      tasks (001–031) plus 5 Phase 3 tasks (040–044) plus the project wrap-up (090). The
      project shipped: a chat-driven "Summarize a Document" vertical slice, Insights
      tool integration (`insights.query`) consuming the Insights r2 Wave F contract,
      session-scoped AI Search infrastructure (`spaarke-session-files` index), and a
      configuration-only `/analyze` proof point validating the platform-extension claim
      (SC-19). R5 is the FIRST Spaarke project to deliver an operationally complete
      Spaarke Assistant — chat agent hosting two AI tool capabilities alongside the
      existing ad-hoc grounded-LLM mode. The lessons-learned doc is therefore unusually
      load-bearing for R6 planning: it captures the working pattern + the rough edges.

      Per CLAUDE.md §7, this is also where the project archives the wrap-up convention.
      The doc is consumed by (a) task 090 as project-status-flip evidence, (b) R6
      project initialization as backlog seed, (c) the broader engineering team as a
      retrospective artifact accessible from `projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/lessons-learned.md`.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="043" status="must-be-complete">
        D3-04 Operator-led end-to-end testing — produces `notes/testing-pass-results.md`
        which seeds the R6 backlog section with severity-ranked findings carried
        forward.
      </dependency>
    </dependencies>
    <related-work>
      <item>R5 task notes folder `projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/`
        is the primary evidence mine — every R5 task that produced ephemeral evidence
        (deployment outputs, smoke-test responses, BFF publish-size measurements, ADR
        compliance walks) stored those files here.</item>
      <item>`insights-r2-coordination.md` §8 changelog tracks Wave F + integration
        touchpoint outcomes — primary source for the surprises section's
        "contract-negotiation outcomes" and "schema-plumbing spike results"
        sub-sections.</item>
      <item>Task 090 (project wrap-up) reads this lessons-learned doc as evidence
        that the project closeout convention is satisfied, then flips the project
        README status from "In Progress" to "Complete", updates the coordination doc
        §8 changelog with the R5 completion entry, and opens the R5 PR against
        master. Task 044 does NOT flip the status — that's 090's job.</item>
      <item>R6 project (whenever initialized) will read the R6 backlog section here
        as its seed inventory.</item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Context Check + Rigor Declaration">
      Check context usage. If &gt; 70%, create handoff summary and request `/compact`.
      Declare RIGOR LEVEL: STANDARD per CLAUDE.md §8 (documentation task; no code; no
      build verification; no quality gates at Step 9.5). Confirm dependency: task 043
      must be ✅ before this task runs (testing-pass-results.md must exist).
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Review Progress">
      Read `tasks/TASK-INDEX.md` and confirm task 044 status is 🔲, dependency on 043
      is ✅, parallel-safe = false. Confirm 043 produced `notes/testing-pass-results.md`.
      Read `current-task.md` to verify task 043 was the most-recently-completed task
      and is properly handed off.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Gather Resources">
      Read all files listed in &lt;inputs&gt;. Specifically extract: (a) D3-05 plan.md
      deliverable description; (b) CLAUDE.md §7 wrap-up convention; (c) project-CLAUDE.md
      §11 lessons-learned pointer; (d) design.md deferred items + R6 candidates; (e)
      spec.md UR-01..UR-05 items + any not-closed by R5 acceptance.

      Walk the `notes/` folder and inventory every per-task evidence file. Specifically
      look for: publish-size deltas (per CLAUDE.md §10 verification mandate), Wave F
      coordination touchpoints (Insights r2 status changes), D1–D6 Insights contract
      decisions recorded in design-e3-tool-call-contract.md §10 review log,
      Structured Outputs streaming behavior observations from task 006 evidence, tool
      routing disambiguation observations from tasks 030 + 031 + 043,
      `citations[].href` schema-plumbing spike outcome from Insights Wave F.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Enumerate Lessons by Phase">
      For each of the 3 phases, draft 3–6 lesson vignettes (2–4 sentences each) covering
      what worked, what surprised, what would be done differently next time. Phase 1
      lessons emphasize platform-extension hygiene (additive event types, additive
      RagSearchOptions parameter, idempotent Bicep, session-files cleanup
      IHostedService, Structured Outputs spike outcome). Phase 2 lessons emphasize the
      vertical-slice + Insights-tool-integration pattern (one-endpoint-per-capability
      with internal routing, two-path response renderer for playbook vs RAG vs decline
      vs empty, 12-error-code handling rigor, R5-lead contract sign-off gate). Phase 3
      lessons emphasize platform-extension validation (`/analyze` proof point cost vs
      target), telemetry observability uptake, operator-led testing pass findings.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Enumerate Surprises">
      Explicit "did NOT go as planned" section. Mine candidates from: (a) Wave F
      Insights r2 v1.1 contract negotiation outcome — did Wave F deploy ahead of /
      alongside / behind R5 Phase 2 W3 need? Did `citations[].href` schema-plumbing
      spike land in v1.1 or defer to v1.2? (b) BFF publish-size deltas — did R5 stay
      under the +0.5 MB target / +1 MB budget / 60 MB ceiling? Which task surprised by
      adding more than expected? (c) Structured Outputs (D1-06) — did Azure OpenAI
      streaming behavior match expectation per plan.md high-risk item #1? (d) Tool
      routing disambiguation between `summarize` and `insights.query` — did the
      LLM tool-call routing produce misroutes? Per plan.md high-risk #4 + spec UR-01.
      (e) `StructuredOutputStreamWidget` schema-driven complexity — was UR-02
      complexity manageable in practice? (f) Any task that escalated to human input
      per CLAUDE.md §6. Frame each surprise with a tight root-cause line + a "what
      we'd do differently" line.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Enumerate R6 Backlog Candidates">
      Compile the R6 backlog inventory. MUST include the items explicitly enumerated
      in the task prompt: (a) Tier 3 file grounding (large-doc summarization on
      uploaded files exceeding context window); (b) editor widget; (c) extracted-text
      widget; (d) additional playbooks beyond Summarize + analyze; (e) any UR-01..UR-05
      items not closed during R5; (f) testing-pass severity-2/3 findings carried
      forward from task 043. Add any net-new candidates surfaced during R5 execution
      (e.g., per-tenant dedicated session-files index if Phase 1 spike recommended
      it; v1.2 `citations[].href` document-URL plumbing if Insights deferred it from
      v1.1; cost telemetry dashboards expansion if Phase 3 dashboards revealed gaps).
      Format each item: ID + 1-sentence intent + driver (what surfaced it) + suggested
      phase placement (foundational / capability / polish).
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Operator Review Stub Section">
      Add the "Operator observations" section as an empty stub with a header note:
      "Operator review: drafted by AI agent; operator adds personal observations
      below before sign-off." Include 4–6 prompt sub-headings to guide operator
      input: (i) Personal observations on AI/human collaboration cadence during R5;
      (ii) Process improvements for R6; (iii) Skill effectiveness (task-execute +
      adr-check + code-review + context-handoff); (iv) Cross-project coordination
      (Insights r2 Wave F coordination quality); (v) Reuse mandate compliance
      observation (did R5 actually avoid rebuilding existing platform pieces?);
      (vi) Anything else worth capturing.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Write the Document">
      Create `projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/lessons-learned.md`.
      Document structure:

      ```
      # Lessons Learned — Spaarke AI Platform Unification R5

      > Status: Draft (AI-authored; awaiting operator review + sign-off)
      > Created: {today's date}
      > Authors: AI Agent (initial draft) + Operator (review + observations)

      ## 1. Executive Summary
      {2–3 paragraphs: project shape, what shipped, headline lessons}

      ## 2. Lessons by Phase

      ### Phase 1 — Platform Extensions
      {3–6 lesson vignettes}

      ### Phase 2 — Vertical Slice + Insights Tool Integration
      {3–6 lesson vignettes}

      ### Phase 3 — Polish + Future-Use Validation
      {3–6 lesson vignettes}

      ## 3. Surprises — What Did NOT Go As Planned
      {Itemized: each surprise has Context → Root Cause → What We'd Do Differently}

      ## 4. R6 Backlog Candidates
      {Itemized table: ID | Intent | Driver | Suggested phase placement}

      ## 5. Operator Observations
      {Stub section with prompt sub-headings; operator fills in during review}

      ## 6. Sign-off
      {Operator records sign-off here; AI agent leaves blank line for operator}
      ```

      Use absolute markdown links to source artifacts where relevant (task POMLs,
      coordination doc, contract docs). Length target: ~800–1500 lines of prose +
      structured items — substantive but not bloated.
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="Operator Review">
      Present the drafted document to the operator. Request: (a) review the lessons +
      surprises + R6 backlog for accuracy + completeness; (b) add personal observations
      in §5; (c) record sign-off in §6 with the operator's name + date. The AI agent
      MUST WAIT for operator confirmation before marking the task complete — this is
      explicitly a collaborative artifact per CLAUDE.md §7 convention.

      If operator requests revisions: apply revisions, re-present, repeat until
      operator records sign-off.
    </step>
    <step order="9" name="Verify Acceptance Criteria">
      Walk through every &lt;acceptance-criterion&gt; below. Confirm: (a) doc exists at
      the canonical path; (b) all 4 mandatory sections present (lessons by phase /
      surprises / R6 backlog / operator observations + sign-off); (c) all 3 phases
      covered in the lessons section; (d) surprises section is explicit (not soft); (e)
      R6 backlog enumerates the 6 mandatory item categories; (f) operator review +
      sign-off recorded. Per STANDARD rigor: Step 9.5 quality gates (code-review +
      adr-check) are SKIPPED per CLAUDE.md §8.
    </step>
    <step order="10" name="Document + Complete">
      Update task POML status to `complete`. Update `TASK-INDEX.md`: 044 🔲 → ✅. Reset
      `current-task.md` per CLAUDE.md §7 — set to task 090 (project wrap-up) as the
      next pending task. Report task completion to the operator. Note explicitly: this
      task does NOT flip the project status to Complete; task 090 handles the actual
      status flip + R5 PR open + merge. Final task notes: confirm BFF publish-size
      delta = 0 MB (no BFF code modified by this task); confirm no Dataverse changes;
      confirm STANDARD rigor was applied per CLAUDE.md §8 decision tree.
    </step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="Read">Read all input files + task evidence in notes/ folder</tool>
    <tool name="Write">Create the lessons-learned.md document</tool>
    <tool name="Edit">Apply operator revisions during review iterations</tool>
    <tool name="Grep">Search task evidence files for specific signals (publish-size deltas, ADR compliance notes, Wave F status, etc.)</tool>
    <tool name="Glob">Inventory task evidence files in notes/ folder</tool>
    <tool name="git">Stage + commit the new lessons-learned doc on the R5 branch (operator-led commit; task 044 does NOT auto-commit)</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="docs">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/lessons-learned.md (NEW; final R5 closeout artifact)</output>
    <output type="docs">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md (status: 044 🔲 → ✅)</output>
    <output type="docs">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/current-task.md (reset; next task = 090)</output>
    <output type="report">Task completion report (per task-execute template Step 6)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">`projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/lessons-learned.md` exists at the canonical path.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Document contains an "Executive Summary" section (§1).</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Document contains a "Lessons by Phase" section (§2) with explicit sub-sections for ALL THREE phases (Phase 1 Platform Extensions, Phase 2 Vertical Slice + Insights Tool Integration, Phase 3 Polish + Future-Use Validation).</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Document contains a "Surprises — What Did NOT Go As Planned" section (§3) with explicit framing — soft hedging is not acceptable. Surprises explicitly cover contract-negotiation outcomes (Wave F v1.1), schema-plumbing spike results (`citations[].href`), BFF publish-size deltas vs the +0.5 MB target, Structured Outputs streaming behavior (D1-06), and tool-routing disambiguation observations.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Document contains an "R6 Backlog Candidates" section (§4) that explicitly enumerates the six mandatory item categories: (a) Tier 3 file grounding; (b) editor widget; (c) extracted-text widget; (d) additional playbooks; (e) UR-01..UR-05 items not closed; (f) testing-pass findings carried forward from task 043.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Document contains an "Operator Observations" section (§5) with prompt sub-headings to guide the operator's personal observations.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Document contains a "Sign-off" section (§6) with the operator's recorded sign-off (name + date).</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Operator has reviewed the document and recorded sign-off in §6. Without operator sign-off the task is NOT complete.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">All file-path references in the document use the canonical `infrastructure/ai-search/` form, NOT the legacy `infra/ai-search/` form.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`TASK-INDEX.md` shows task 044 status flipped from 🔲 to ✅; `current-task.md` is reset to task 090.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Task notes confirm: BFF publish-size delta = 0 MB (no BFF code modified); no Dataverse changes; STANDARD rigor applied per CLAUDE.md §8; quality gates at Step 9.5 SKIPPED per rigor level.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Task 044 does NOT flip the project README status to Complete — that is explicitly task 090's responsibility. Task 044's acceptance is "project status ready to flip" only.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
